An **array** in C is a collection of data items of the same data type, stored at contiguous memory locations. It's one of the simplest and most fundamental data structures. Arrays are useful for storing a fixed number of elements of the same type.

### Array Declaration and Initialization:

Arrays can be declared with a specified size, or initialized directly, in which case the compiler deduces the size.

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    // 1. Declaration with fixed size (elements initialized to garbage values or zeros if global/static)
    int numbers[5]; // Declares an integer array that can hold 5 elements

    // 2. Initialization after declaration by accessing elements
    numbers[0] = 10; // First element (index 0)
    numbers[1] = 20;
    numbers[2] = 30;
    numbers[3] = 40;
    numbers[4] = 50; // Last element (index 4)

    // 3. Declaration and initialization at once (compiler determines size)
    double scores[] = { 90.5, 88.0, 92.3, 78.9 }; 

    // 4. Accessing elements (arrays are 0-indexed)
    printf("First number: %d\n", numbers[0]); // Output: 10
    printf("Third score: %.1lf\n", scores[2]);   // Output: 92.3

    // 5. Modifying an element
    numbers[2] = 35;
    printf("Modified numbers[2]: %d\n", numbers[2]); // Output: 35

    // 6. Getting array length (using sizeof) - works for arrays in the same scope
    // size_t is an unsigned integer type returned by sizeof
    size_t numbers_length = sizeof(numbers) / sizeof(numbers[0]);
    size_t scores_length = sizeof(scores) / sizeof(scores[0]);
    printf("Length of numbers array: %zu\n", numbers_length); // Output: 5
    printf("Length of scores array: %zu\n", scores_length); // Output: 4

    // 7. Iterating through an array using a for loop
    printf("\nElements of numbers array:\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < numbers_length; i++) {
        printf("numbers[%d] = %d\n", i, numbers[i]);
    }

    return 0;
}
```

* **Zero-indexed:** Array elements are always accessed starting from index `0`.
* **Fixed Size:** Once an array is created, its size is fixed at compile time. You cannot resize it during runtime. For dynamic collections, you would use dynamic memory allocation (pointers) or more advanced data structures (like linked lists).
* **`sizeof` Operator:** The `sizeof` operator can be used to calculate the size of an array in bytes. Dividing it by the size of a single element gives the number of elements.

### Multi-dimensional Arrays (e.g., 2D Arrays/Matrices):

Arrays can have more than one dimension. A two-dimensional array is often used to represent a table or a matrix.

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    // Declare and initialize a 2D array (2 rows, 3 columns)
    int matrix[2][3] = {
        {1, 2, 3}, // Row 0
        {4, 5, 6}  // Row 1
    };

    // Accessing elements in a 2D array
    printf("Element at matrix[0][1]: %d\n", matrix[0][1]); // Output: 2

    // Iterating through a 2D array using nested loops
    printf("\nMatrix elements:\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++) { // Loop through rows
        for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) { // Loop through columns
            printf("%d ", matrix[i][j]);
        }
        printf("\n"); // Newline after each row
    }

    return 0;
}
```

Arrays are a fundamental data structure for storing ordered collections of similar data.

codeExamples.code:
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int ages[3] = {25, 30, 22};
    printf("Ages: %d, %d, %d\n", ages[0], ages[1], ages[2]);

    // Change an element
    ages[1] = 31;
    printf("Updated second age: %d\n", ages[1]);

    return 0;
}

