In C, a **structure** (`struct`) is a user-defined data type that allows you to combine variables of different data types under a single name. Structures are incredibly useful for representing real-world entities that have multiple attributes, such as a `Student` (with `name`, `id`, `grade`), a `Point` (with `x`, `y` coordinates), or a `Book` (with `title`, `author`, `pages`).

### Declaring a Structure:

* A structure definition creates a blueprint or a template for a new data type. It does not allocate memory.
* **Syntax:**
    ```c
    struct StructureName {
        dataType member1;
        dataType member2;
        // ... more members
    };
    ```

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

// 1. Declare a structure named 'Student'
struct Student {
    char name[50];
    int roll_number;
    float marks;
};

int main() {
    // 2. Declare variables of type 'struct Student'
    struct Student student1; // Declare a structure variable

    // 3. Accessing and assigning values to members (using the dot operator '.')
    strcpy(student1.name, "Alice Smith"); // Assign string using strcpy
    student1.roll_number = 101;
    student1.marks = 85.5f;

    // 4. Accessing and printing members
    printf("Student Name: %s\n", student1.name);
    printf("Roll Number: %d\n", student1.roll_number);
    printf("Marks: %.1f\n", student1.marks);

    // 5. Another way to initialize structures upon declaration
    struct Student student2 = {"Bob Johnson", 102, 92.0f};
    printf("\nStudent Name: %s\n", student2.name);
    printf("Roll Number: %d\n", student2.roll_number);
    printf("Marks: %.1f\n", student2.marks);

    return 0;
}
```

### Accessing Members:

* **Dot Operator (`.`):** Used to access members of a structure variable directly (e.g., `student1.name`).
* **Arrow Operator (`->`):** Used to access members of a structure when working with a **pointer to a structure** (e.g., `ptr_to_student->name`).

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

struct Point {
    int x;
    int y;
};

int main() {
    struct Point p1 = {10, 20};
    struct Point *ptr_p1 = &p1; // Pointer to a Point structure

    // Accessing members using dot operator
    printf("p1.x = %d, p1.y = %d\n", p1.x, p1.y);

    // Accessing members using arrow operator with a pointer
    printf("ptr_p1->x = %d, ptr_p1->y = %d\n", ptr_p1->x, ptr_p1->y);

    // Modifying through pointer
    ptr_p1->x = 15;
    printf("p1.x after modification via pointer = %d\n", p1.x);

    return 0;
}
```

### `typedef` with Structures (Convenience):

Using `typedef` can create an alias for `struct StructureName`, making variable declarations cleaner.

```c
#include <stdio.h>

// Define a structure and create a typedef alias 'Circle'
typedef struct Circle {
    float radius;
    char color[20];
} Circle; // Now 'Circle' can be used instead of 'struct Circle'

int main() {
    Circle c1; // Declare using the typedef alias
    c1.radius = 10.0f;
    // strcpy(c1.color, "Red"); // Can't use strcpy without string.h

    printf("Circle radius: %.1f\n", c1.radius);

    return 0;
}
```

Structures are essential for creating complex, organized data types that mirror real-world entities, forming the basis for more advanced data structures like linked lists and trees.

codeExamples.code:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

// Define a structure for a Book
struct Book {
    char title[100];
    char author[50];
    int pages;
    double price;
};

int main() {
    // Declare and initialize a Book variable
    struct Book myBook = {"The Great Adventure", "John Writer", 300, 25.99};

    // Print book details
    printf("Book Title: %s\n", myBook.title);
    printf("Author: %s\n", myBook.author);
    printf("Pages: %d\n", myBook.pages);
    printf("Price: $%.2lf\n", myBook.price);

    // Create another book and assign values individually
    struct Book anotherBook;
    strcpy(anotherBook.title, "C Programming Basics");
    strcpy(anotherBook.author, "Code Master");
    anotherBook.pages = 450;
    anotherBook.price = 39.95;

    printf("\nAnother Book Title: %s\n", anotherBook.title);

    return 0;
}

