A **union** in C is a special user-defined data type that allows you to store different data types in the *same memory location*. Unlike structures, where each member has its own distinct memory, all members of a union share the same memory space. This means a union can hold *only one* of its members' values at any given time.

### Theoretical Aspects of Unions:

* **Memory Sharing:** The size of a union is determined by the size of its largest member. All members are stored starting at the same memory address within that allocated space.
* **Single Active Member:** You can only use one member of a union at a time. If you assign a value to one member, and then assign a value to another, the previous member's value will be overwritten.
* **Purpose:** Unions are primarily used for memory optimization in specific scenarios where you know that only one piece of information (of different possible types) will be needed at any given moment for a particular object.

### Declaring and Using a Union:

* The syntax for declaring a union is similar to a structure, but with the `union` keyword.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

// Declare a union named 'Data'
union Data {
    int i;       // Integer member
    float f;     // Float member
    char str[20]; // Character array (string) member
};

int main() {
    union Data data; // Declare a union variable

    printf("Size of union Data: %zu bytes (size of its largest member, str[20])\n", sizeof(data));

    // 1. Assign value to integer member 'i'
    data.i = 10; 
    printf("Data.i: %d\n", data.i); // Output: Data.i: 10
    printf("Data.f: %f (Garbage or 0.0 because 'i' overwrites 'f')\n", data.f); // Undefined behavior if accessed after 'i' assigned

    // 2. Assign value to float member 'f' (this overwrites 'i')
    data.f = 22.5f;
    printf("Data.f: %f\n", data.f); // Output: Data.f: 22.500000
    printf("Data.i: %d (Garbage because 'f' overwrites 'i')\n", data.i); // Undefined behavior

    // 3. Assign value to string member 'str' (this overwrites 'f')
    strcpy(data.str, "Hello Union");
    printf("Data.str: %s\n", data.str); // Output: Data.str: Hello Union
    printf("Data.i: %d (Garbage because 'str' overwrites 'i')\n", data.i); // Undefined behavior
    printf("Data.f: %f (Garbage because 'str' overwrites 'f')\n", data.f); // Undefined behavior

    return 0;
}
```

### `union` vs. `struct` (Key Differences):

| Feature    | `struct`                                | `union`                                   |
| :--------- | :-------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------- |
| **Memory** | Each member has its own memory location | All members share the same memory location|
| **Size** | Sum of sizes of all members (plus padding) | Size of the largest member                 |
| **Usage** | All members can hold values simultaneously | Only one member can hold a valid value at a time |
| **Purpose**| Group related but distinct data         | Memory optimization where only one type is active |

### When to Use Unions:

* **Memory Optimization:** In embedded systems or memory-constrained environments where you need to save space and know that at any given time, only one type of data will be active.
* **Type Punning:** (Advanced and generally discouraged for portability) To interpret the same memory block as different data types. For example, to inspect the individual bytes of an `int`.

```c
#include <stdio.h>

// Example of type punning (advanced, use with caution)
union IntBytes {
    int i;
    char bytes[sizeof(int)]; // Array of chars to view individual bytes
};

int main() {
    union IntBytes ib;
    ib.i = 0x12345678; // Example integer value

    printf("Integer: 0x%X\n", ib.i);
    printf("Bytes (Hex, depending on endianness):\n");
    for (size_t k = 0; k < sizeof(int); k++) {
        printf("Byte %zu: 0x%02X\n", k, (unsigned char)ib.bytes[k]);
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Unions are a niche but powerful feature in C, allowing for memory-efficient data representation when carefully managed.

codeExamples.code:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

// Union for a flexible ID type
union ID {
    int int_id;
    char string_id[20];
};

int main() {
    union ID employeeID;

    // Store an integer ID
    employeeID.int_id = 12345;
    printf("Integer ID: %d\n", employeeID.int_id);

    // Now store a string ID (this overwrites the integer ID)
    strcpy(employeeID.string_id, "EMP_A001");
    printf("String ID: %s\n", employeeID.string_id);

    // Accessing int_id now would be undefined behavior/garbage
    printf("Integer ID (after string): %d\n", employeeID.int_id); 

    return 0;
}

